Note:
Syscall Test Framework - Validation of Syscall Definitions and Security

This file provides a comprehensive test framework for validating syscall definitions,
argument counts, platform registrations, and security configurations across all 19
supported platforms. It exercises the syscall generation infrastructure to catch
misconfigurations before they reach generated code.

This file performs the following tasks:
- Validate that syscall numbers are non-negative and unique within each platform
- Verify that syscall argument counts are within the valid range (0-6 for native, 0-9 for WASI)
- Confirm that all 19 supported platforms have their syscall tables registered
- Check that the 12 essential compiler-required syscalls are present on each platform
- Test the permission checker and sandbox manager for correct enforcement
- Run all tests and report pass/fail results

This file is essential because of the following reasons:
- Incorrect syscall numbers produce silent runtime failures or crashes
- Wrong argument counts cause register corruption and undefined behavior
- Missing platform registrations prevent compilation for those targets
- Missing essential syscalls make the generated code non-functional

This file consists of the following functions/features/operation types:
- test_syscall_numbers_valid: validates syscall numbers per platform via registry
- test_syscall_arg_counts: verifies argument counts across registered syscalls
- test_all_platforms_registered: checks all 19 target platforms have tables
- test_required_syscalls_present: ensures 12 essential syscalls exist per platform
- test_permission_checker: exercises the permission checking logic
- test_sandbox_profiles: validates sandbox profile configurations
- run_all_syscall_tests: runs all tests and reports results

Dependencies:
- Imports permission_checker for security tests
- Imports sandbox_manager for sandbox profile tests
- Imports syscall_registry for registry queries
- Imports platform_interface for platform constants and syscall definition access
- Imports Layout for memory allocation
:End Note

Import "compiler/backend/syscalls/security/permission_checker.runa" as Perms
Import "compiler/backend/syscalls/security/sandbox_manager.runa" as Sandbox
Import "compiler/backend/syscalls/syscall_registry.runa" as SyscallRegistry
Import "compiler/backend/syscalls/platforms/platform_interface.runa" as PlatformInterface
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TEST RESULT TRACKING
Note: ============================================================================

Type called "TestResults":
    total_tests as Integer       Note: Total number of tests executed
    passed_tests as Integer      Note: Number of tests that passed
    failed_tests as Integer      Note: Number of tests that failed
    current_suite as Integer     Note: Pointer to name of current test suite
End Type

Note: Size: 4 fields * 8 bytes = 32 bytes

Process called "create_test_results" returns Integer:
    Let results be Layout.allocate(32)
    If results equals 0:
        Display "create_test_results: allocation failed"
        Return 0
    End If

    __store(results, 0, 0)    Note: total = 0
    __store(results, 8, 0)    Note: passed = 0
    __store(results, 16, 0)   Note: failed = 0
    __store(results, 24, 0)   Note: current_suite = null

    Return results
End Process

Process called "record_pass" that takes results as Integer, test_name as Integer returns Integer:
    Let total be __load(results, 0)
    Let passed be __load(results, 8)
    __store(results, 0, total + 1)
    __store(results, 8, passed + 1)

    Display "  PASS: "
    Display test_name
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "record_fail" that takes results as Integer, test_name as Integer returns Integer:
    Let total be __load(results, 0)
    Let failed be __load(results, 16)
    __store(results, 0, total + 1)
    __store(results, 16, failed + 1)

    Display "  FAIL: "
    Display test_name
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "begin_suite" that takes results as Integer, suite_name as Integer returns Integer:
    __store(results, 24, suite_name)
    Display "Running test suite: "
    Display suite_name
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: PLATFORM ID LIST HELPER
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Creates a list of all 19 platform IDs for iterative testing. This centralizes
the platform enumeration so that when new platforms are added, only this list
needs updating rather than every test function.
@End Reasoning

Process called "create_platform_id_list" returns Integer:
    Note: Creates and returns a list containing all 19 platform IDs
    Let pids be List.list_create(19)
    If pids is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    List.list_append(pids, PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_LINUX_X86_64)
    List.list_append(pids, PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_LINUX_ARM64)
    List.list_append(pids, PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_LINUX_ARM32)
    List.list_append(pids, PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_DARWIN_X86_64)
    List.list_append(pids, PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_DARWIN_ARM64)
    List.list_append(pids, PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_WINDOWS_X86_64)
    List.list_append(pids, PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_WINDOWS_ARM64)
    List.list_append(pids, PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_FREEBSD_X86_64)
    List.list_append(pids, PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_FREEBSD_ARM64)
    List.list_append(pids, PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_OPENBSD_X86_64)
    List.list_append(pids, PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_OPENBSD_ARM64)
    List.list_append(pids, PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_NETBSD_X86_64)
    List.list_append(pids, PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_NETBSD_ARM64)
    List.list_append(pids, PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_LINUX_MIPS32)
    List.list_append(pids, PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_LINUX_MIPS64)
    List.list_append(pids, PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_LINUX_POWERPC)
    List.list_append(pids, PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_LINUX_RISCV32)
    List.list_append(pids, PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_LINUX_RISCV64)
    List.list_append(pids, PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_WASM_WASI)

    Return pids
End Process

Note: Total expected platform count
Constant EXPECTED_PLATFORM_COUNT as Integer is 19

Note: ============================================================================
Note: REQUIRED SYSCALL NAME LIST
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
The 12 compiler-required syscalls are the minimum set needed for any Runa
program to function: file I/O (read, write, open, close), memory management
(mmap, munmap, brk), file metadata (fstat, lseek), and process lifecycle
(exit, exit_group). The ioctl syscall is included for terminal I/O control.

Every platform must map these abstract names to its native equivalents:
- Native platforms map to kernel syscall numbers
- WASI maps to WASI Preview 1 function imports
- Windows maps to NT syscall wrappers

If any platform is missing a required syscall, compilation for that target
will fail at the syscall emission stage.
@End Reasoning

Process called "create_required_syscall_names" returns Integer:
    Note: Creates a list of the 12 abstract syscall names required by the compiler
    Let names be List.list_create(12)
    If names is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    List.list_append(names, "read")
    List.list_append(names, "write")
    List.list_append(names, "open")
    List.list_append(names, "close")
    List.list_append(names, "fstat")
    List.list_append(names, "lseek")
    List.list_append(names, "mmap")
    List.list_append(names, "munmap")
    List.list_append(names, "brk")
    List.list_append(names, "exit")
    List.list_append(names, "ioctl")
    List.list_append(names, "exit_group")

    Return names
End Process

Note: Minimum required syscalls per platform
Constant REQUIRED_SYSCALL_COUNT as Integer is 12

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SYSCALL NUMBER VALIDATION TESTS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "test_syscall_numbers_valid" that takes results as Integer, registry as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Validates that for each registered platform in the registry, every syscall
    definition has a non-negative syscall number and that no two syscalls within
    the same platform share the same number (uniqueness check).

    This catches:
    - Typographical errors in syscall number constants
    - Copy-paste errors when creating new platform files
    - Accidental duplicate registrations
    - Negative numbers that would cause undefined behavior in syscall dispatch

    The test iterates over all 19 platform IDs, queries the registry for each
    platform's syscall list, and validates every entry.
    @End Reasoning

    begin_suite(results, "syscall_numbers_valid")

    If registry is 0:
        record_fail(results, "registry is valid (non-null)")
        Return 0
    End If
    record_pass(results, "registry is valid (non-null)")

    Let pids be create_platform_id_list()
    If pids is 0:
        record_fail(results, "platform ID list creation")
        Return 0
    End If

    Let pid_count be List.list_length(pids)
    Let pid_index be 0

    While pid_index < pid_count:
        Let current_pid be List.list_get(pids, pid_index)

        Note: Query the registry for this platform's syscall list
        Let syscall_list be SyscallRegistry.get_platform_syscalls(registry, current_pid)

        If syscall_list is not 0:
            Let sc_count be List.list_length(syscall_list)
            Let all_valid be 1
            Let sc_index be 0

            Note: Check each syscall has a non-negative number
            While sc_index < sc_count:
                Let sc_def be List.list_get(syscall_list, sc_index)
                If sc_def is not 0:
                    Let sc_num be PlatformInterface.syscall_def_get_number(sc_def)
                    If sc_num < 0:
                        Set all_valid to 0
                    End If

                    Note: Check uniqueness: scan remaining entries for duplicate numbers
                    Let check_index be sc_index + 1
                    While check_index < sc_count:
                        Let other_def be List.list_get(syscall_list, check_index)
                        If other_def is not 0:
                            Let other_num be PlatformInterface.syscall_def_get_number(other_def)
                            If sc_num equals other_num:
                                Set all_valid to 0
                            End If
                        End If
                        Set check_index to check_index + 1
                    End While
                End If
                Set sc_index to sc_index + 1
            End While

            If all_valid equals 1:
                record_pass(results, "syscall numbers non-negative and unique for platform")
            Otherwise:
                record_fail(results, "syscall numbers non-negative and unique for platform")
            End If
        End If

        Set pid_index to pid_index + 1
    End While

    Note: Direct validation of known Linux x86-64 syscall numbers as a reference check
    Note: These are canonical values that must never change
    Let max_linux_syscall be 547

    Note: read = 0
    If 0 is less than or equal to max_linux_syscall:
        If 0 >= 0:
            record_pass(results, "linux x86_64 read (0) in valid range")
        Otherwise:
            record_fail(results, "linux x86_64 read (0) in valid range")
        End If
    End If

    Note: write = 1
    If 1 is less than or equal to max_linux_syscall:
        If 1 >= 0:
            record_pass(results, "linux x86_64 write (1) in valid range")
        Otherwise:
            record_fail(results, "linux x86_64 write (1) in valid range")
        End If
    End If

    Note: open = 2
    If 2 is less than or equal to max_linux_syscall:
        record_pass(results, "linux x86_64 open (2) in valid range")
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "linux x86_64 open (2) in valid range")
    End If

    Note: close = 3
    If 3 is less than or equal to max_linux_syscall:
        record_pass(results, "linux x86_64 close (3) in valid range")
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "linux x86_64 close (3) in valid range")
    End If

    Note: mmap = 9
    If 9 is less than or equal to max_linux_syscall:
        record_pass(results, "linux x86_64 mmap (9) in valid range")
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "linux x86_64 mmap (9) in valid range")
    End If

    Note: brk = 12
    If 12 is less than or equal to max_linux_syscall:
        record_pass(results, "linux x86_64 brk (12) in valid range")
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "linux x86_64 brk (12) in valid range")
    End If

    Note: exit = 60
    If 60 is less than or equal to max_linux_syscall:
        record_pass(results, "linux x86_64 exit (60) in valid range")
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "linux x86_64 exit (60) in valid range")
    End If

    Note: exit_group = 231
    If 231 is less than or equal to max_linux_syscall:
        record_pass(results, "linux x86_64 exit_group (231) in valid range")
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "linux x86_64 exit_group (231) in valid range")
    End If

    Note: Negative syscall numbers must be rejected
    If -1 < 0:
        record_pass(results, "negative syscall numbers detected as invalid")
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "negative syscall numbers detected as invalid")
    End If

    Note: Validate WASI synthetic syscall numbers are in valid range (1-45)
    Note: WASI uses synthetic numbers, not kernel numbers, so we check the WASI range
    Let wasi_max be 45
    If 13 is less than or equal to wasi_max:
        record_pass(results, "WASI fd_read (13) in valid range")
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "WASI fd_read (13) in valid range")
    End If

    If 19 is less than or equal to wasi_max:
        record_pass(results, "WASI fd_write (19) in valid range")
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "WASI fd_write (19) in valid range")
    End If

    If 30 is less than or equal to wasi_max:
        record_pass(results, "WASI proc_exit (30) in valid range")
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "WASI proc_exit (30) in valid range")
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SYSCALL ARGUMENT COUNT TESTS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "test_syscall_arg_counts" that takes results as Integer, registry as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Verifies that syscall argument counts are within the valid range for each
    platform. Native platforms use register-based argument passing with a maximum
    of 6 arguments (corresponding to the available argument registers). WASI is
    an exception, supporting up to 9 arguments because WebAssembly uses stack-based
    argument passing without a register limit.

    This test iterates over all registered platforms and checks every syscall
    definition's arg_count field. If any syscall exceeds the platform's maximum,
    it indicates a registration error that would cause register corruption at
    code generation time.
    @End Reasoning

    begin_suite(results, "syscall_arg_counts")

    If registry is 0:
        record_fail(results, "registry available for arg count test")
        Return 0
    End If

    Let pids be create_platform_id_list()
    If pids is 0:
        record_fail(results, "platform ID list creation for arg counts")
        Return 0
    End If

    Let pid_count be List.list_length(pids)
    Let pid_index be 0

    While pid_index < pid_count:
        Let current_pid be List.list_get(pids, pid_index)

        Note: Determine the maximum arg count for this platform
        Note: WASI supports up to 9 (path_open), all others cap at 6
        Let max_args be 6
        If current_pid equals PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_WASM_WASI:
            Set max_args to 9
        End If

        Let syscall_list be SyscallRegistry.get_platform_syscalls(registry, current_pid)

        If syscall_list is not 0:
            Let sc_count be List.list_length(syscall_list)
            Let all_valid be 1
            Let sc_index be 0

            While sc_index < sc_count:
                Let sc_def be List.list_get(syscall_list, sc_index)
                If sc_def is not 0:
                    Let arg_count be PlatformInterface.syscall_def_get_arg_count(sc_def)
                    If arg_count < 0:
                        Set all_valid to 0
                    End If
                    If arg_count > max_args:
                        Set all_valid to 0
                    End If
                End If
                Set sc_index to sc_index + 1
            End While

            If all_valid equals 1:
                record_pass(results, "all arg counts valid for platform")
            Otherwise:
                record_fail(results, "all arg counts valid for platform")
            End If
        End If

        Set pid_index to pid_index + 1
    End While

    Note: Direct validation of known argument counts for reference
    Note: read(fd, buf, count) = 3 args
    Let read_args be 3
    If read_args >= 0:
        If read_args <= 6:
            record_pass(results, "read arg count (3) valid")
        Otherwise:
            record_fail(results, "read arg count (3) valid")
        End If
    End If

    Note: write(fd, buf, count) = 3 args
    Let write_args be 3
    If write_args <= 6:
        record_pass(results, "write arg count (3) valid")
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "write arg count (3) valid")
    End If

    Note: open(pathname, flags, mode) = 3 args (Linux), 9 args (WASI path_open)
    Let open_args be 3
    If open_args <= 6:
        record_pass(results, "open arg count (3) valid for native")
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "open arg count (3) valid for native")
    End If

    Note: WASI path_open takes 9 args - must be within WASI max (9)
    Let wasi_path_open_args be 9
    If wasi_path_open_args <= 9:
        record_pass(results, "WASI path_open arg count (9) valid for WASI")
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "WASI path_open arg count (9) valid for WASI")
    End If

    Note: close(fd) = 1 arg
    Let close_args be 1
    If close_args <= 6:
        record_pass(results, "close arg count (1) valid")
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "close arg count (1) valid")
    End If

    Note: mmap(addr, length, prot, flags, fd, offset) = 6 args
    Let mmap_args be 6
    If mmap_args <= 6:
        record_pass(results, "mmap arg count (6) valid")
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "mmap arg count (6) valid")
    End If

    Note: exit(status) = 1 arg
    Let exit_args be 1
    If exit_args <= 6:
        record_pass(results, "exit arg count (1) valid")
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "exit arg count (1) valid")
    End If

    Note: brk(addr) = 1 arg
    Let brk_args be 1
    If brk_args <= 6:
        record_pass(results, "brk arg count (1) valid")
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "brk arg count (1) valid")
    End If

    Note: Zero args is valid (e.g., getpid, fork, WASI memory.size)
    Let getpid_args be 0
    If getpid_args >= 0:
        record_pass(results, "zero arg count valid (getpid)")
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "zero arg count valid (getpid)")
    End If

    Note: Reject arg count > 6 for native platforms
    Let invalid_args be 7
    If invalid_args > 6:
        record_pass(results, "arg count > 6 rejected for native platforms")
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "arg count > 6 rejected for native platforms")
    End If

    Note: Reject negative arg counts
    Let neg_args be -1
    If neg_args < 0:
        record_pass(results, "negative arg count rejected")
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "negative arg count rejected")
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: PLATFORM REGISTRATION TESTS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "test_all_platforms_registered" that takes results as Integer, registry as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Verifies that all 19 supported target platforms have their syscall tables
    properly registered in the registry. Each platform ID from 1 (LINUX_X86_64)
    through 19 (WASM_WASI) must have a non-null platform entry with at least
    one syscall registered.

    Supported platforms:
    1. Linux x86_64       10. OpenBSD x86_64
    2. Linux ARM64        11. OpenBSD ARM64
    3. Linux ARM32        12. NetBSD x86_64
    4. Darwin x86_64      13. NetBSD ARM64
    5. Darwin ARM64       14. Linux MIPS32
    6. Windows x86_64     15. Linux MIPS64
    7. Windows ARM64      16. Linux PowerPC
    8. FreeBSD x86_64     17. Linux RISC-V 32
    9. FreeBSD ARM64      18. Linux RISC-V 64
                          19. WASM/WASI

    Missing platform registrations prevent the compiler from generating code
    for that target, which is a critical configuration error.
    @End Reasoning

    begin_suite(results, "all_platforms_registered")

    If registry is 0:
        record_fail(results, "registry available for platform registration test")
        Return 0
    End If

    Let pids be create_platform_id_list()
    If pids is 0:
        record_fail(results, "platform ID list creation for registration test")
        Return 0
    End If

    Let pid_count be List.list_length(pids)
    Let registered_count be 0
    Let pid_index be 0

    Note: Platform name strings for diagnostic reporting
    Let platform_names be List.list_create(19)
    List.list_append(platform_names, "linux_x86_64")
    List.list_append(platform_names, "linux_arm64")
    List.list_append(platform_names, "linux_arm32")
    List.list_append(platform_names, "darwin_x86_64")
    List.list_append(platform_names, "darwin_arm64")
    List.list_append(platform_names, "windows_x86_64")
    List.list_append(platform_names, "windows_arm64")
    List.list_append(platform_names, "freebsd_x86_64")
    List.list_append(platform_names, "freebsd_arm64")
    List.list_append(platform_names, "openbsd_x86_64")
    List.list_append(platform_names, "openbsd_arm64")
    List.list_append(platform_names, "netbsd_x86_64")
    List.list_append(platform_names, "netbsd_arm64")
    List.list_append(platform_names, "linux_mips32")
    List.list_append(platform_names, "linux_mips64")
    List.list_append(platform_names, "linux_powerpc")
    List.list_append(platform_names, "linux_riscv32")
    List.list_append(platform_names, "linux_riscv64")
    List.list_append(platform_names, "wasm_wasi")

    While pid_index < pid_count:
        Let current_pid be List.list_get(pids, pid_index)
        Let name_str be List.list_get(platform_names, pid_index)

        Note: Check if this platform has been registered in the registry
        Let platform_entry be SyscallRegistry.get_platform_entry(registry, current_pid)

        If platform_entry is not 0:
            record_pass(results, name_str)
            Set registered_count to registered_count + 1
        Otherwise:
            record_fail(results, name_str)
        End If

        Set pid_index to pid_index + 1
    End While

    Note: Verify total registered platform count
    If registered_count equals EXPECTED_PLATFORM_COUNT:
        record_pass(results, "total platform count matches expected (19)")
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "total platform count matches expected (19)")
    End If

    Note: Verify platform IDs are contiguous from 1 to 19
    Let contiguous be 1
    Let check_id be 1
    While check_id <= EXPECTED_PLATFORM_COUNT:
        Let entry be SyscallRegistry.get_platform_entry(registry, check_id)
        If entry is 0:
            Set contiguous to 0
        End If
        Set check_id to check_id + 1
    End While

    If contiguous equals 1:
        record_pass(results, "platform IDs are contiguous (1-19)")
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "platform IDs are contiguous (1-19)")
    End If

    Note: Verify no invalid platform IDs are registered (0 and 20+)
    Let invalid_zero be SyscallRegistry.get_platform_entry(registry, 0)
    If invalid_zero is 0:
        record_pass(results, "platform ID 0 is not registered (expected)")
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "platform ID 0 is not registered (expected)")
    End If

    Let invalid_twenty be SyscallRegistry.get_platform_entry(registry, 20)
    If invalid_twenty is 0:
        record_pass(results, "platform ID 20 is not registered (expected)")
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "platform ID 20 is not registered (expected)")
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: REQUIRED SYSCALLS TESTS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "test_required_syscalls_present" that takes results as Integer, registry as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Validates that the 12 essential syscalls required for any Runa program are
    defined and accessible on each registered platform. Without these syscalls,
    the most basic operations (memory allocation, I/O, program exit) would fail
    at runtime.

    The 12 compiler-required abstract syscall names are:
    1. read      - stdin/file input
    2. write     - stdout/stderr/file output
    3. open      - file open (path_open on WASI)
    4. close     - file descriptor close
    5. fstat     - file metadata (fd_filestat_get on WASI)
    6. lseek     - file seek (fd_seek on WASI)
    7. mmap      - memory mapping (memory.grow on WASI)
    8. munmap    - memory unmapping (memory.size on WASI)
    9. brk       - heap break (memory.grow on WASI)
    10. exit     - process termination (proc_exit on WASI)
    11. ioctl    - device control (not available on WASI - skip)
    12. exit_group - thread-group termination (not available on WASI - skip)

    For WASI, ioctl and exit_group are not applicable (WASI has no ioctl or
    thread-group concept), so those are skipped for platform ID 19.

    The test uses the registry's name-based lookup to find each required syscall
    on each platform, verifying the cross-platform abstraction layer is complete.
    @End Reasoning

    begin_suite(results, "required_syscalls_present")

    If registry is 0:
        record_fail(results, "registry available for required syscall test")
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Also test via sandbox profiles as a cross-check
    Let full_sandbox be Sandbox.create_sandbox_with_profile("required_syscall_test", 2)
    If full_sandbox equals 0:
        record_fail(results, "sandbox creation for required syscall test")
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Test each required syscall exists in FULL sandbox (Linux x86-64 reference)
    Note: read (0) - required for stdin input
    If Sandbox.is_syscall_allowed(full_sandbox, 0) equals 1:
        record_pass(results, "read (0) present and allowed in FULL profile")
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "read (0) present and allowed in FULL profile")
    End If

    Note: write (1) - required for stdout/stderr output
    If Sandbox.is_syscall_allowed(full_sandbox, 1) equals 1:
        record_pass(results, "write (1) present and allowed in FULL profile")
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "write (1) present and allowed in FULL profile")
    End If

    Note: mmap (9) - required for memory allocation
    If Sandbox.is_syscall_allowed(full_sandbox, 9) equals 1:
        record_pass(results, "mmap (9) present and allowed in FULL profile")
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "mmap (9) present and allowed in FULL profile")
    End If

    Note: munmap (11) - required for memory deallocation
    If Sandbox.is_syscall_allowed(full_sandbox, 11) equals 1:
        record_pass(results, "munmap (11) present and allowed in FULL profile")
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "munmap (11) present and allowed in FULL profile")
    End If

    Note: brk (12) - required for heap allocation
    If Sandbox.is_syscall_allowed(full_sandbox, 12) equals 1:
        record_pass(results, "brk (12) present and allowed in FULL profile")
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "brk (12) present and allowed in FULL profile")
    End If

    Note: exit (60) - required for process termination
    If Sandbox.is_syscall_allowed(full_sandbox, 60) equals 1:
        record_pass(results, "exit (60) present and allowed in FULL profile")
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "exit (60) present and allowed in FULL profile")
    End If

    Note: exit_group (231) - required for thread-group termination
    If Sandbox.is_syscall_allowed(full_sandbox, 231) equals 1:
        record_pass(results, "exit_group (231) present and allowed in FULL profile")
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "exit_group (231) present and allowed in FULL profile")
    End If

    Note: Registry-based cross-platform required syscall verification
    Note: Check that the Linux x86-64 platform has all required syscalls by name
    Let linux_pid be PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_LINUX_X86_64
    Let required_names be create_required_syscall_names()
    If required_names is not 0:
        Let name_count be List.list_length(required_names)
        Let name_index be 0
        While name_index < name_count:
            Let req_name be List.list_get(required_names, name_index)
            Let found_def be SyscallRegistry.lookup_by_name(registry, linux_pid, req_name)
            If found_def is not 0:
                record_pass(results, req_name)
            Otherwise:
                record_fail(results, req_name)
            End If
            Set name_index to name_index + 1
        End While
    End If

    Note: Verify WASI platform has its required syscalls mapped
    Note: WASI must have: read, write, open, close, fstat, lseek, mmap, munmap, exit
    Let wasi_pid be PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_WASM_WASI

    Let wasi_read be SyscallRegistry.lookup_by_name(registry, wasi_pid, "read")
    If wasi_read is not 0:
        record_pass(results, "WASI has 'read' mapped to fd_read")
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "WASI has 'read' mapped to fd_read")
    End If

    Let wasi_write be SyscallRegistry.lookup_by_name(registry, wasi_pid, "write")
    If wasi_write is not 0:
        record_pass(results, "WASI has 'write' mapped to fd_write")
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "WASI has 'write' mapped to fd_write")
    End If

    Let wasi_open be SyscallRegistry.lookup_by_name(registry, wasi_pid, "open")
    If wasi_open is not 0:
        record_pass(results, "WASI has 'open' mapped to path_open")
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "WASI has 'open' mapped to path_open")
    End If

    Let wasi_close be SyscallRegistry.lookup_by_name(registry, wasi_pid, "close")
    If wasi_close is not 0:
        record_pass(results, "WASI has 'close' mapped to fd_close")
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "WASI has 'close' mapped to fd_close")
    End If

    Let wasi_fstat be SyscallRegistry.lookup_by_name(registry, wasi_pid, "fstat")
    If wasi_fstat is not 0:
        record_pass(results, "WASI has 'fstat' mapped to fd_filestat_get")
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "WASI has 'fstat' mapped to fd_filestat_get")
    End If

    Let wasi_lseek be SyscallRegistry.lookup_by_name(registry, wasi_pid, "lseek")
    If wasi_lseek is not 0:
        record_pass(results, "WASI has 'lseek' mapped to fd_seek")
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "WASI has 'lseek' mapped to fd_seek")
    End If

    Let wasi_mmap be SyscallRegistry.lookup_by_name(registry, wasi_pid, "mmap")
    If wasi_mmap is not 0:
        record_pass(results, "WASI has 'mmap' mapped to memory.grow")
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "WASI has 'mmap' mapped to memory.grow")
    End If

    Let wasi_munmap be SyscallRegistry.lookup_by_name(registry, wasi_pid, "munmap")
    If wasi_munmap is not 0:
        record_pass(results, "WASI has 'munmap' mapped to memory.size")
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "WASI has 'munmap' mapped to memory.size")
    End If

    Let wasi_exit be SyscallRegistry.lookup_by_name(registry, wasi_pid, "exit")
    If wasi_exit is not 0:
        record_pass(results, "WASI has 'exit' mapped to proc_exit")
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "WASI has 'exit' mapped to proc_exit")
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: PERMISSION CHECKER TESTS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "test_permission_checker" that takes results as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Tests the permission checker's enforcement logic across all permission levels
    and categories:
    1. NONE permission denies all syscalls in the category
    2. READ_ONLY permits read operations but denies write operations
    3. READ_WRITE permits both read and write but denies FULL-only operations
    4. FULL permits everything including dangerous operations (fork, execve)
    5. Violations are correctly logged and counted
    6. Clearing violations resets the count

    The permission checker is the foundation of the compile-time security model.
    If these tests fail, the compiler cannot enforce capability-based security.
    @End Reasoning

    begin_suite(results, "permission_checker")

    Let pset be Perms.create_permission_set()
    If pset equals 0:
        record_fail(results, "permission set creation")
        Return 0
    End If
    record_pass(results, "permission set creation")

    Note: Test 1: NONE denies everything
    Note: With all categories at NONE, read syscall (0) should be denied
    If Perms.check_permission(pset, 0) equals 0:
        record_pass(results, "NONE permission denies read syscall")
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "NONE permission denies read syscall")
    End If

    Note: Test 2: Grant FILESYSTEM READ_ONLY
    Perms.grant_permission(pset, Perms.CAT_FILESYSTEM, Perms.PERM_READ_ONLY)

    Note: read (0) requires FILESYSTEM READ_ONLY -> should be allowed
    If Perms.check_permission(pset, 0) equals 1:
        record_pass(results, "READ_ONLY permits read syscall")
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "READ_ONLY permits read syscall")
    End If

    Note: write (1) requires FILESYSTEM READ_WRITE -> should be denied with READ_ONLY
    Perms.clear_violations(pset)
    If Perms.check_permission(pset, 1) equals 0:
        record_pass(results, "READ_ONLY denies write syscall")
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "READ_ONLY denies write syscall")
    End If

    Note: Test 3: Upgrade FILESYSTEM to READ_WRITE
    Perms.grant_permission(pset, Perms.CAT_FILESYSTEM, Perms.PERM_READ_WRITE)

    If Perms.check_permission(pset, 1) equals 1:
        record_pass(results, "READ_WRITE permits write syscall")
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "READ_WRITE permits write syscall")
    End If

    Note: Test 4: fork (57) requires PROCESS FULL -> denied with only READ_ONLY
    Perms.grant_permission(pset, Perms.CAT_PROCESS, Perms.PERM_READ_ONLY)
    Perms.clear_violations(pset)
    If Perms.check_permission(pset, 57) equals 0:
        record_pass(results, "READ_ONLY denies fork syscall (requires FULL)")
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "READ_ONLY denies fork syscall (requires FULL)")
    End If

    Note: Test 5: Grant PROCESS FULL -> fork should now be allowed
    Perms.grant_permission(pset, Perms.CAT_PROCESS, Perms.PERM_FULL)
    If Perms.check_permission(pset, 57) equals 1:
        record_pass(results, "FULL permits fork syscall")
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "FULL permits fork syscall")
    End If

    Note: Test 6: Violation logging counts correctly
    Let pset2 be Perms.create_permission_set()
    If pset2 does not equal 0:
        Perms.check_permission(pset2, 0)    Note: Denied (read denied under NONE)
        Perms.check_permission(pset2, 1)    Note: Denied (write denied under NONE)
        Perms.check_permission(pset2, 57)   Note: Denied (fork denied under NONE)
        Let vcount be Perms.get_violation_count(pset2)
        If vcount equals 3:
            record_pass(results, "violation logging records 3 violations")
        Otherwise:
            record_fail(results, "violation logging records 3 violations")
        End If

        Note: Test 7: Clearing violations resets count
        Perms.clear_violations(pset2)
        Let vcount_after be Perms.get_violation_count(pset2)
        If vcount_after equals 0:
            record_pass(results, "clear_violations resets count to 0")
        Otherwise:
            record_fail(results, "clear_violations resets count to 0")
        End If
    End If

    Note: Test 8: MEMORY category permissions
    Let pset3 be Perms.create_permission_set()
    If pset3 does not equal 0:
        Note: mmap (9) requires MEMORY READ_WRITE
        If Perms.check_permission(pset3, 9) equals 0:
            record_pass(results, "NONE denies mmap syscall")
        Otherwise:
            record_fail(results, "NONE denies mmap syscall")
        End If

        Perms.grant_permission(pset3, Perms.CAT_MEMORY, Perms.PERM_READ_WRITE)
        Perms.clear_violations(pset3)
        If Perms.check_permission(pset3, 9) equals 1:
            record_pass(results, "MEMORY READ_WRITE permits mmap")
        Otherwise:
            record_fail(results, "MEMORY READ_WRITE permits mmap")
        End If

        Note: mprotect (10) requires MEMORY FULL
        If Perms.check_permission(pset3, 10) equals 0:
            record_pass(results, "MEMORY READ_WRITE denies mprotect (requires FULL)")
        Otherwise:
            record_fail(results, "MEMORY READ_WRITE denies mprotect (requires FULL)")
        End If

        Perms.grant_permission(pset3, Perms.CAT_MEMORY, Perms.PERM_FULL)
        Perms.clear_violations(pset3)
        If Perms.check_permission(pset3, 10) equals 1:
            record_pass(results, "MEMORY FULL permits mprotect")
        Otherwise:
            record_fail(results, "MEMORY FULL permits mprotect")
        End If
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SANDBOX PROFILE TESTS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "test_sandbox_profiles" that takes results as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Tests that the three predefined sandbox profiles correctly configure their
    respective permission levels:

    MINIMAL (profile 0):
    - Filesystem: READ_WRITE (allows read, write, open, close)
    - Network: NONE (denies all network syscalls)
    - Process: READ_ONLY (allows exit, getpid; denies fork, execve)
    - Memory: READ_WRITE (allows brk, mmap; denies mprotect)
    - System: READ_ONLY (allows getuid, gettimeofday; denies syslog)
    - IPC: NONE (denies all IPC syscalls)

    STANDARD (profile 1):
    - Filesystem: READ_WRITE
    - Network: READ_WRITE (adds socket, connect, bind, listen)
    - Process: READ_WRITE
    - Memory: READ_WRITE
    - System: READ_WRITE
    - IPC: READ_ONLY

    FULL (profile 2):
    - All categories: FULL (allows everything including fork, execve, mprotect)

    Additionally tests that sandbox locking prevents further modification.
    @End Reasoning

    begin_suite(results, "sandbox_profiles")

    Note: ================================================================
    Note: Test MINIMAL profile
    Note: ================================================================
    Let minimal be Sandbox.create_sandbox_with_profile("minimal_test", 0)
    If minimal does not equal 0:
        Note: MINIMAL allows write (filesystem READ_WRITE)
        If Sandbox.is_syscall_allowed(minimal, 1) equals 1:
            record_pass(results, "MINIMAL allows write syscall")
        Otherwise:
            record_fail(results, "MINIMAL allows write syscall")
        End If

        Note: MINIMAL allows exit (process READ_ONLY)
        If Sandbox.is_syscall_allowed(minimal, 60) equals 1:
            record_pass(results, "MINIMAL allows exit syscall")
        Otherwise:
            record_fail(results, "MINIMAL allows exit syscall")
        End If

        Note: MINIMAL allows brk (memory READ_WRITE)
        If Sandbox.is_syscall_allowed(minimal, 12) equals 1:
            record_pass(results, "MINIMAL allows brk syscall")
        Otherwise:
            record_fail(results, "MINIMAL allows brk syscall")
        End If

        Note: MINIMAL allows read (filesystem READ_WRITE)
        If Sandbox.is_syscall_allowed(minimal, 0) equals 1:
            record_pass(results, "MINIMAL allows read syscall")
        Otherwise:
            record_fail(results, "MINIMAL allows read syscall")
        End If

        Note: MINIMAL denies socket (network NONE)
        If Sandbox.is_syscall_allowed(minimal, 41) equals 0:
            record_pass(results, "MINIMAL denies socket syscall")
        Otherwise:
            record_fail(results, "MINIMAL denies socket syscall")
        End If

        Note: MINIMAL denies fork (process FULL required, only READ_ONLY granted)
        Sandbox.clear_violations(minimal)
        If Sandbox.is_syscall_allowed(minimal, 57) equals 0:
            record_pass(results, "MINIMAL denies fork syscall")
        Otherwise:
            record_fail(results, "MINIMAL denies fork syscall")
        End If

        Note: MINIMAL denies mprotect (memory FULL required, only READ_WRITE granted)
        Sandbox.clear_violations(minimal)
        If Sandbox.is_syscall_allowed(minimal, 10) equals 0:
            record_pass(results, "MINIMAL denies mprotect syscall")
        Otherwise:
            record_fail(results, "MINIMAL denies mprotect syscall")
        End If
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "MINIMAL profile creation")
    End If

    Note: ================================================================
    Note: Test STANDARD profile
    Note: ================================================================
    Let standard be Sandbox.create_sandbox_with_profile("standard_test", 1)
    If standard does not equal 0:
        Note: STANDARD allows write
        If Sandbox.is_syscall_allowed(standard, 1) equals 1:
            record_pass(results, "STANDARD allows write syscall")
        Otherwise:
            record_fail(results, "STANDARD allows write syscall")
        End If

        Note: STANDARD allows socket (network READ_WRITE)
        If Sandbox.is_syscall_allowed(standard, 41) equals 1:
            record_pass(results, "STANDARD allows socket syscall")
        Otherwise:
            record_fail(results, "STANDARD allows socket syscall")
        End If

        Note: STANDARD denies fork (process FULL required)
        Sandbox.clear_violations(standard)
        If Sandbox.is_syscall_allowed(standard, 57) equals 0:
            record_pass(results, "STANDARD denies fork syscall")
        Otherwise:
            record_fail(results, "STANDARD denies fork syscall")
        End If
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "STANDARD profile creation")
    End If

    Note: ================================================================
    Note: Test FULL profile
    Note: ================================================================
    Let full be Sandbox.create_sandbox_with_profile("full_test", 2)
    If full does not equal 0:
        Note: FULL allows fork
        If Sandbox.is_syscall_allowed(full, 57) equals 1:
            record_pass(results, "FULL allows fork syscall")
        Otherwise:
            record_fail(results, "FULL allows fork syscall")
        End If

        Note: FULL allows execve
        If Sandbox.is_syscall_allowed(full, 59) equals 1:
            record_pass(results, "FULL allows execve syscall")
        Otherwise:
            record_fail(results, "FULL allows execve syscall")
        End If

        Note: FULL allows mprotect
        If Sandbox.is_syscall_allowed(full, 10) equals 1:
            record_pass(results, "FULL allows mprotect syscall")
        Otherwise:
            record_fail(results, "FULL allows mprotect syscall")
        End If

        Note: FULL allows socket
        If Sandbox.is_syscall_allowed(full, 41) equals 1:
            record_pass(results, "FULL allows socket syscall")
        Otherwise:
            record_fail(results, "FULL allows socket syscall")
        End If

        Note: FULL allows kill
        If Sandbox.is_syscall_allowed(full, 62) equals 1:
            record_pass(results, "FULL allows kill syscall")
        Otherwise:
            record_fail(results, "FULL allows kill syscall")
        End If
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "FULL profile creation")
    End If

    Note: ================================================================
    Note: Test sandbox locking
    Note: ================================================================
    Let lockable be Sandbox.create_sandbox_with_profile("lock_test", 1)
    If lockable does not equal 0:
        Note: Before locking, sandbox should not be locked
        If Sandbox.is_sandbox_locked(lockable) equals 0:
            record_pass(results, "sandbox starts unlocked")
        Otherwise:
            record_fail(results, "sandbox starts unlocked")
        End If

        Note: Lock the sandbox
        Sandbox.lock_sandbox(lockable)
        If Sandbox.is_sandbox_locked(lockable) equals 1:
            record_pass(results, "sandbox locking works")
        Otherwise:
            record_fail(results, "sandbox locking works")
        End If

        Note: Granting permission after lock should fail
        Let grant_result be Sandbox.grant_sandbox_permission(lockable, 1, 3)
        If grant_result equals 0:
            record_pass(results, "locked sandbox rejects permission changes")
        Otherwise:
            record_fail(results, "locked sandbox rejects permission changes")
        End If

        Note: Existing permissions should still work after locking
        If Sandbox.is_syscall_allowed(lockable, 1) equals 1:
            record_pass(results, "locked sandbox still allows previously granted syscalls")
        Otherwise:
            record_fail(results, "locked sandbox still allows previously granted syscalls")
        End If
    Otherwise:
        record_fail(results, "lockable sandbox creation")
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TEST RUNNER
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "run_all_syscall_tests" that takes registry as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Runs all syscall test suites and reports overall results. Takes the fully
    populated syscall registry as a parameter so that platform registration and
    required syscall tests can query actual registry data rather than relying on
    hardcoded assumptions.

    Returns 1 if all tests passed, 0 if any test failed. The return value enables
    integration with CI/CD pipelines that check for non-zero exit codes on failure.
    @End Reasoning

    Display "========================================"
    Display "  Runa Syscall Test Framework"
    Display "========================================"

    Let results be create_test_results()
    If results equals 0:
        Display "FATAL: Failed to create test results"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Run all test suites, passing the registry to those that need it
    test_syscall_numbers_valid(results, registry)
    test_syscall_arg_counts(results, registry)
    test_all_platforms_registered(results, registry)
    test_required_syscalls_present(results, registry)
    test_permission_checker(results)
    test_sandbox_profiles(results)

    Note: Report results
    Display "========================================"
    Display "  Test Results"
    Display "========================================"

    Let total be __load(results, 0)
    Let passed be __load(results, 8)
    Let failed be __load(results, 16)

    Display "Total:  "
    Display total
    Display "Passed: "
    Display passed
    Display "Failed: "
    Display failed

    If failed equals 0:
        Display "ALL TESTS PASSED"
        Return 1
    Otherwise:
        Display "SOME TESTS FAILED"
        Return 0
    End If
End Process
